---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Navigation from "../../components/Navigation.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";
---

<Layout title="DailyDine Case Study">
  <Navigation />

  <main id="main-content" class="flex-1 max-w-[72ch] mx-auto px-6 py-16 sm:py-24 flex flex-col gap-12 font-sans">
    
    <!-- Header -->
    <header class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <div class="flex gap-2 text-xs text-[#71717A] font-mono">
        <span>Work</span>
        <span>·</span>
        <span>Case Study</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-display font-medium text-[#FAFAFA] tracking-tight leading-tight">
        DailyDine
      </h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-[#A1A1AA] italic">
        "Build things that still make sense a decade later."
      </p>
    </header>

    <!-- Case Study Content -->
    <div class="flex flex-col gap-12 text-[#FAFAFA] text-base leading-[1.7] tracking-tight font-normal">
      
      <!-- Overview -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Overview</h2>
        <p>
          DailyDine coordinates table reservations for local restaurants, focusing on scheduling reliability.
          The utility coordinates dining schedules and prevents double bookings.
          It serves as a clean alternative to bloated, third-party coordination tools.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Challenge -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Challenge</h2>
        <p>
          The system must balance venue capacity limits with customer dining requests.
          Peak times introduce concurrent writes that can lead to overbooking.
          Resolving this issue requires strict inventory tracking without compromising scheduling speed.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Approach -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Approach</h2>
        <p>
          I designed a queuing model that processes reservation updates sequentially.
          The queue locks inventory elements while a transaction compiles.
          This prevents race conditions and ensures transaction integrity under high write load.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Architecture -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Architecture</h2>
        <p>
          The backend runs on Go, utilizing a PostgreSQL instance for transactional persistence.
          The client uses a minimal React interface built with Tailwind CSS.
          API communication uses strict JSON payloads for predictable parsing.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Trade-offs -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Trade-offs</h2>
        <p>
          I chose server-side polling instead of WebSockets to reduce active database connections.
          This increases client network calls slightly but reduces server memory allocation.
          Simple HTTP polling remains robust and easier to scale than persistent socket connections.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Outcome -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Outcome</h2>
        <p>
          The platform successfully processes reservations across local venues.
          Double booking incidents have been completely eliminated.
          The simplicity of the database schema has kept runtime latencies minimal.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Lessons -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Lessons</h2>
        <p>
          Simple database transactions are easier to maintain than distributed state machines.
          Over-engineering early in product design adds unnecessary maintenance overhead.
          Clear database design is often the most reliable solution.
        </p>
      </section>

    </div>

    <!-- Tech Stack footer -->
    <footer class="flex flex-col gap-6 border-t border-[rgba(255,255,255,0.08)] pt-8 mt-4 text-xs font-mono text-[#71717A]">
      <span>Technologies: Go · React · PostgreSQL · Tailwind CSS</span>
    </footer>

  </main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
